webpackJsonp([18824660024201],{4849:function(e,t){e.exports={pathContext:{group:[{node:{fields:{title:"Ooops!",date:"08 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-08-ooops/",tags:"Y2000"},html:'<p>I managed to break my Internet server so that I can no longer log in over the network. Since it is in Maryland and I am in Germany, it is a bit inpractical for me to log in directly! So until my hosting service can help me out, the <a href="http://www.mausnews.de">Maus Newsletter</a> is down, and E-mail sent to shcon.con or mausnews.de isn\'t being delivered. In the meantime, we can be reached at <a href="mailto:shanson@freenet.de">shanson@freenet.de</a> <b>Update Sunday 9 Jan 4 pm</b> The machine is back up! I\'ll slowly get everything running again.</p>'},next:{fields:{title:"He's now official",date:"07 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-07-hes-now-official/"}},previous:{fields:{title:"Reflections on childbirth",date:"09 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-09-reflections-on-childbirth/"}}},{node:{fields:{title:"He's now official",date:"07 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-07-hes-now-official/",tags:"Y2000"},html:'<p>We finally took the baby carriage out for a spin this afternoon. Of course, I left the camera inside, but here you can see Christopher all bundled up for the ride.</p>\n<p><img src="http://www.papascott.de/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2000/01/crh0107.jpg" height="300" width="400" border="0" alt="crh0107.jpg: " /></p>\n<p>Now that we have Christopher\'s papers, we can start our tour of German bureaucracy.</p>\n<p>At our local city hall, I registered Christopher\'s official residence and had a exemption added to my income tax card. I also changed my tax status from secondary earner to main earner, since Mama is on maternity leave this year.</p>\n<p>The first eight weeks of maternity leave are paid, and the unpaid leave can last until the child turns 3, during which the mother and father can alternate. As part of maternity leave, Mama receives a \'Child Rearing Payment\' of DM 600 for 6 months.  Low income families receive this for 2 years. The application is more complicated than a tax return!</p>\n<p>From the federal labor ministry, we will receive a monthly \'Kindergeld\' until Christropher is at least 18, even longer if he studies or learns a trade. The SPD/Green government just increased the Kindergeld by DM 20 to DM 270 per month (about $140).</p>\n<p>From the social security office comes a one-time \'Maternity Payment\' of DM 400 as a supplement to the paid maternity leave.</p>'},next:{fields:{title:"He's now official",date:"06 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-06-hes-now-official/"}},previous:{fields:{title:"Ooops!",date:"08 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-08-ooops/"}}},{node:{fields:{title:"He's now official",date:"06 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-06-hes-now-official/",tags:"Y2000"},html:'<p>Is it just me, or does a German birth certificate look more like a prescription than an official document?</p>\n<p><img src="http://www.papascott.de/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2000/01/urkunde.jpg" height="623" width="400" border="0" alt="urkunde.jpg: " /></p>\n<p>At least it\'s cheap: DM 24, or $15. The <a href="http://www.usconsulate.de">US Consulate</a> wants $40 to register the birth to an American citizen abroad, and then another $40 for a child\'s passport.</p>'},next:{fields:{title:"Christopher Ryan Hanson",date:"05 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-05-christopher-ryan-hanson/"}},previous:{fields:{title:"He's now official",date:"07 Jan 2000",slug:"/2000-01-07-hes-now-official/"}}}],pathPrefix:"",first:!1,last:!1,index:1092,pageCount:1101}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---1092-925c1a72f7b1bd5a377d.js.map